</mei>
<!--
VOICING PLAN:
- Phrase 1 (mm. 1-8): Root-position G and D triads in LH ("33" / "334"). RH stays in 2-note
  figures (thirds and sixths) to avoid doubling the melody. C and Em always root pos.
- Phrase 2 (mm. 9-16): LH upgrades to "333" maj7 on G for warmth; D7 for tension.
  RH uses "43" 1st inversions for variety; quartal "44" on D for open modern sound (m.13).
- Phrase 4 (mm. 17-26): F#° vii° in LH uses "33" triad; G "334" extended for climax (m.21).
  Penultimate m.25 uses suspension: G→D in RH over G→D in LH for a double dominant.

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- Measures 2, 10: LH bass descends E2→B2→C2→G2 (chromatic-adjacent stepwise).
- Measure 7 (and 15): RH ascending countermelody G4→B4→A4→C5 against descending melody.
- Measure 10: RH inner voice descends B4→A4→G4→F#4 contrary to static bass.
- Measure 19: RH doubles melody at the unison then diverges to E5 — voice exchange.
- Measure 22 (F#°): half-step B3→C3 resolution in LH subverts listener's expectation.

TEXTURE ARC:
- mm. 1-4: Open, two-note RH figures, half-note LH block chords. Establishes the hymn.
- mm. 5-8: D7 pedal creates tension; quartal RH color at m.6/7. Release on G.
- mm. 9-16: Repeat with richer LH (maj7, "43" inv); more independent RH lines.
- mm. 17-20: Shorter chord durations per bar (3-4 LH chords), increased harmonic rhythm.
- mm. 21-22: Climax — G Δ7 in LH, high G5 RH; then sudden vii° for color.
- mm. 23-26: Convergence: simpler quarter-note LH, RH descends, final G in all registers.
-->
